Problem 1:

\(X \sim U(0,1)\) and \(Y \sim U(0,1)\).

Plot the joint distribution of X & Y such that \(X+Y < 1\)

Numerical Example

\(\left(X_1, X_2\right)\) with the range \(\left\{\left(x_1, x_2\right) \mid x_1 \geq 0, x_2 \geq 0, x_1+x_2 \leq 1\right\}\) and the joint desity function \(f\left(x_1, x_2\right)=2\) on this range.

  1. First make a large number of samples from \(X \sim U(0,1)\) and \(Y \sim U(0,1)\) and plot X & Y and then plot the samples below the line \(x+y = 1\) .
set.seed(1000)
x <- replicate(10000, runif(1, min = 0, max = 1))

y <- replicate(10000, runif(1, min = 0, max = 1))

data <- data.frame(x, y)

plot(data$x, data$y, pch = 20, col = "lightgreen", xlab = "X", ylab = "Y", main = "Scatter Plot of X and Y")

plot(data$x < 0.5, data$y < 0.5 , pch = 20, col = "lightgreen", xlab = "X", ylab = "Y", main = "Scatter Plot of X and Y with x+y=1")

abline(1,-1 , col = "red")


points(data$x[data$x + data$y < 1], data$y[data$x + data$y < 1], pch = 20, col = "gold")

  1. By looking at the plot, what is the joint p.d.f \(f(X,Y)\)?
  • The region below the line \((x + y = 1)\) is a triangle with vertices at (0,0), (1,0), and (0,1). The area of this triangle is 0.5, as it is half of a unit square.

Since the joint probability density function (p.d.f.) integrates to 1 over the entire range, we can define the joint p.d.f. of X and Y as:

\[f(X, Y) = \begin{cases} 2 & \text{for } 0 \leq X \leq 1, 0 \leq Y \leq 1, \text{ and } X + Y \leq 1 \\0 & \text{otherwise}\end{cases}\]

  1. Find the marginal distribution of X by hand and making a probability histogram. Compare whether these are the same. (Hint: think about the limits of X and Y according to \(0<X+Y<1\))

  • \[0 < X + Y < 1\]

    integrating \(f(X, Y)\) with respect to Y: \[f_X(X) = \int_{{0}}^{{1-X}} 2 \, dy\]

    \[f_X(X) = 2\left[y\right]_{{0}}^{{1-X}} = 2(1-X)\]

    The marginal distribution of X is:

    \[f_X(X) = 2(1-X)\]

fx <- 2 - 2*x

hist(x[x+y<1], breaks = 20, xlab = 'X', ylab = 'Density', main = 'Marginal distribution of X')

The Marginal Distribution of X by hand and the probability histogram display the same results.

  1. Find the marginal distribution of Y by hand and making a probability histogram. Compare whether these are the same. (Hint: think about the limits of X and Y according to \(0<X+Y<1\))

  • \[0 < X + Y < 1\]

    integrating \(f(X, Y)\) with respect to X:

    \[f_Y(Y) = \int_{{0}}^{{1-Y}} 2 \, dx\]

    \[f_Y(Y) = 2\left[x\right]_{{0}}^{{1-Y}} = 2(1-Y)\]

    So, the marginal distribution of Y is:

    \[f_Y(Y) = 2(1-Y)\]

hist(y[x+y<1], breaks = 20, xlab = 'X', ylab = 'Density', main = 'Marginal distribution of Y')

The Marginal Distribution of Y by hand and the probability histogram display the same results.

Problem 2: Joint distributions and Conditional Expectations.

A CDF is defined by

\[ \begin{aligned} F(x,y) &= \begin{cases} Cx^2y(x+y^2) \quad (0 \leq y \leq 3, 0 \leq x \leq 2)\\ 0 \quad (otherwise) \end{cases} \end{aligned} \]

  1. Find the joint probability density function.

The Probability density function is defined as the derivative of the CDF function

\[ \begin{aligned} &\frac{\partial^2}{\partial x \partial y}\left(C x^2 y\left(x+y^2\right)\right)\\ &\begin{aligned} & \frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(C x^2 y\left(x+y^2\right)\right)=C y\left(3 x^2+2 x y^2\right) \\ & =\frac{\partial}{\partial \boldsymbol{y}}\left(C y\left(3 \boldsymbol{x}^2+2 x y^2\right)\right) \end{aligned}\\ &\begin{aligned} & \frac{\partial}{\partial y}\left(C y\left(3 x^2+2 x y^2\right)\right)=C\left(3 x^2+6 x y^2\right) \\ & =C\left(3 \boldsymbol{x}^2+\mathbf{6 x y}^2\right) \end{aligned} \end{aligned} \]

  1. Find the value of \(C\).

\[ \begin{aligned} &\int_0^3 \int_0^2 C\left(3 x^2+6 x y^2\right) d x d y\\ &\begin{aligned} & \int_0^2 C\left(3 x^2+6 x y^2\right) d x=C\left(8+12 y^2\right) \\ & =\int_{\mathbf{0}}^{\mathbf{3}} \boldsymbol{C}\left(\mathbf{8}+\mathbf{1 2} \boldsymbol{y}^{\mathbf{2}}\right) \boldsymbol{d y} \end{aligned}\\ &\begin{aligned} & \int_0^3 C\left(8+12 y^2\right) d y=132 C \\ & \mathbf{1 3 2 C} = 1 \end{aligned} \end{aligned} \]

\[ C = 1/132 \]

  1. Find the Marginal density of \(X\)

\[ \int_0^3 C\left(3 x^2+6 x y^2\right) d y \] \[Take the constant out: $\int a \cdot f(x) d x=a \cdot \int f(x) d x \] \[ =C \cdot \int_0^3 3 x^2+6 x y^2 d y \] Apply the Sum Rule: \(\int f(x) \pm g(x) d x=\int f(x) d x \pm \int g(x) d x\) \[ \left.=C_( \int_0^3 3 x^2 d y+\int_0^3 6 x y^2 d y\right) \] \[ \int_0^3 3 x^2 d y=9 x^2 \] \[ \int_0^3 6 x y^2 d y=54 x \] \[ =C\left(9 x^2+54 x\right) \]

  1. Find the Conditional expectation \(E(Y|X)\)

\[ \int_0^3 y \frac{3 C x^2+6 C x y^2}{9 C x^2+54 C x} d y \] Take the constant out: \(\int a \cdot f(x) d x=a \cdot \int f(x) d x\) \[ =\frac{1}{54 C x+9 C x^2} \cdot \int_0^3\left(3 C x^2+6 C x y^2\right) y d y \] Expand \(\left(3 C x^2+6 C x y^2\right) y: \quad 3 C x^2 y+6 C x y^3\) \[ =\frac{1}{54 C x+9 C x^2} \cdot \int_0^3 3 C x^2 y+6 C x y^3 d y \] Apply the Sum Rule: \(\int f(x) \pm g(x) d x=\int f(x) d x \pm \int g(x) d x\) \[ =\frac{1}{54 C x+9 C x^2}\left(\int_0^3 3 C x^2 y d y+\int_0^3 6 C x y^3 d y\right) \] \[ \int_0^3 3 C x^2 y d y=\frac{27 C x^2}{2} \] \[ \int_0^3 6 C x y^3 d y=\frac{243 C x}{2} \] \[ =\frac{1}{54 C x+9 C x^2}\left(\frac{27 C x^2}{2}+\frac{243 C x}{2}\right) \] Simplify \(\frac{1}{54 C x+9 C x^2}\left(\frac{27 C x^2}{2}+\frac{243 C x}{2}\right): \quad \frac{3(x+9)}{2(x+6)}\) \[ =\frac{3(x+9)}{2(x+6)} \]

  1. Find the probability \(Pr(X\leq Y)\)

\[ \begin{aligned} &\int_0^2 \int_x^3 3 C x^2+6 C y^2 x d y d x\\ &\begin{aligned} & \int_x^3 3 C x^2+6 C y^2 x d y=9 C x^2-3 C x^3+6 C x\left(9-\frac{x^3}{3}\right) \\ & =\int_0^2\left(9 C x^2-3 C x^3+6 C x\left(9-\frac{x^3}{3}\right)\right) d x \\ & \end{aligned}\\ &\begin{aligned} & \int_0^2\left(9 C x^2-3 C x^3+6 C x\left(9-\frac{x^3}{3}\right)\right) d x=12 C+\frac{476 C}{5} \\ & =\mathbf{1 2 C}+\frac{\mathbf{4 7 6} \boldsymbol{C}}{\mathbf{5}}~=\mathbf{0.832} \end{aligned} \end{aligned} \]
